---
const takeaways = [
  {
    name: "Rust Fundamentals With Real Context",
    desc: "Build a practical foundation in Rust syntax, ownership, borrowing, lifetimes, and idiomatic project structure through Bitcoin-flavored problems.",
  },
  {
    name: "Domain Modeling for Bitcoin",
    desc: "Model transactions, blocks, networks, validation errors, and reusable library APIs that can power miners, nodes, and wallet tools.",
  },
  {
    name: "Production-Style Engineering Habits",
    desc: "Practice testing, error handling, linting, serialization, modular architecture, and clean CLI design using real assignment workflows.",
  },
  {
    name: "Concurrency and Async Skills",
    desc: "Implement multi-threaded CPU mining, then move to async Rust and Tokio for networking and node-style command handling.",
  },
  {
    name: "End-to-End Bitcoin Builder Path",
    desc: "Finish with wallet construction, request/dispatch design, and an extended capstone window to integrate all prior components.",
  },
  {
    name: "Certificate and Community",
    desc: "Earn a completion certificate and continue collaborating with peers, TAs, and mentors on deeper Bitcoin open-source work.",
  },
];
---

<div class="lg:p-8">
  <h1
    class="mb-3 mt-8 font-header text-3xl font-bold md:text-6xl lg:text-6xl"
    id="about_us"
  >
    Building Bitcoin in Rust by Lukáš Hozda
  </h1>

  <p class="font-base text-base md:text-base lg:text-2xl">
    <span class="font-bold text-orange">What is it?</span>
    This is an <strong>11-week Rust cohort</strong> designed for programmers who are new to Rust and want to learn it through a practical Bitcoin-focused build path. The curriculum follows the learning arc of <strong><a
      target="_blank"
      class="underline"
      href="https://braiins.com/books/building-bitcoin-in-rust?lang=en"
      >Building Bitcoin in Rust</a
    ></strong>, starting with Rust setup and fundamentals, then moving through ownership, traits, testing, mining, async networking, node design, and wallet construction.
  </p>

  <p class="my-5 text-base md:text-base lg:text-2xl">
    <span class="font-bold text-orange">Who is it for?</span>
    This cohort is for developers and technical learners who can code in at least one language and want to transition into <span class="font-bold">Rust + Bitcoin systems programming</span>. If you prefer learning by building and want clear weekly structure, this track is for you.
  </p>

  <p class="text-base md:text-base lg:text-2xl">
    <span class="font-bold text-orange">What are the prerequisites?</span>
    Comfort with basic programming concepts (functions, loops, data structures, and debugging) is expected. Prior Rust experience is <strong>not required</strong>. Familiarity with Git and command-line workflows will help. Bitcoin curiosity is required; deep protocol expertise is not.
  </p>

  <div class="my-10">
    <h3 class="my-8 text-2xl font-bold text-orange">
      What are the takeaways?
    </h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 lg:pl-10">
      {
        takeaways.map((takeaway) => (
          <li class="my-4 lg:text-2xl">
            <span class="font-header font-bold">{takeaway.name}</span>: {takeaway.desc}
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p class="text-base md:text-base lg:text-2xl">
    <span class="font-bold text-orange">What is the assignment flow?</span>
    Each week includes one live teaching session and one GitHub Classroom assignment. Assignments are test-driven with visible tests for feedback and may include hidden tests for edge-case grading.
  </p>

  <p class="mt-5 text-base md:text-base lg:text-2xl">
    <span class="font-bold text-orange">Primary reference book:</span>
    <a
      target="_blank"
      class="underline"
      href="https://braiins.com/books/building-bitcoin-in-rust?lang=en"
      >Building Bitcoin in Rust (Braiins)</a
    > by Lukáš Hozda.
  </p>
</div>
